jurors against each other.

00:37.337 --> 00:41.909 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: And Elvis Costello
talks about the moments that
influenced his music and

00:41.909 --> 00:44.378 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
his new autobiography.

00:44.378 --> 00:50.384 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ELVIS COSTELLO, Musician: I am a
fairly decent,
dark-dispositioned person, have
been, but

00:50.384 --> 00:53.654 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
you can -- it can start to like
it, rather than sort of try to
think, well, yes, I'm

00:53.654 --> 00:56.123 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
-- I was fine being a skeptic,
but then when you start to
settle for that, then it's not

00:56.123 --> 00:57.624 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
very good.

00:57.624 --> 01:04.164 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: All that and more
on tonight's "PBS NewsHour."

01:04.164 --> 01:08.602 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
(BREAK)

01:08.602 --> 01:19.112 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: New numbers today
put the enormity of Europe's
migrant surge in stark relief.

01:19.112 --> 01:25.085 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The United Nations Refugee
Agency said more than 218,000
people reached the continent

01:25.085 --> 01:31.892 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
by sea last month. That's
roughly equal to the total for
all of 2014.

01:31.892 --> 01:36.897 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Streams of adults and children
kept trekking across Southern
European borders today, and

01:36.897 --> 01:40.467 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
U.N. officials warned
there's no letup in sight.

01:40.467 --> 01:41.735 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ADRIAN EDWARDS, Spokesman,
United Nations High Commissioner
for Human Rights: We have

01:41.735 --> 01:46.707 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to expect this level of arrival
to continue, and that's because
the factors that are causing

01:46.707 --> 01:50.610 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
people to move
aren't going away.

01:50.610 --> 01:56.717 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We are in a period of record
numbers of forced displacement
globally, almost 60 million
people

01:56.717 --> 02:01.421 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
fleeing conflict, fleeing areas
of instability. It is the new
reality that we all have to

02:01.421 --> 02:05.392 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
deal with, that this is a
phenomenon that isn't going away
quickly.

02:05.392 --> 02:12.165 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: The U.N.
anticipates some 744,000
migrants will arrive in Europe
for all of

02:12.165 --> 02:17.437 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
this year. More than half are
from Syria. At least another
3,400 people have died or

02:17.437 --> 02:20.774 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
disappeared trying
to make the journey.

02:20.774 --> 02:26.279 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Communities in
Colorado and North Carolina are
looking for answers, after
weekend

02:26.279 --> 02:31.818 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
shootings that left five people
dead. In Colorado Springs, on
Saturday, a gunman killed three

02:31.818 --> 02:36.390 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
people in a neighborhood street,
before police killed him. A
local newspaper reports he'd

02:36.390 --> 02:40.594 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
complained online
of mind control.

02:40.594 --> 02:44.931 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And early yesterday at
Winston-Salem State University,
one student was shot dead and

02:44.931 --> 02:49.503 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
another was wounded. The
suspect is a former student.

02:49.503 --> 02:55.575 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: A two-year
bipartisan federal budget deal
has officially become law.
President

02:55.575 --> 03:00.647 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Obama signed it today in a brief
ceremony in the Oval Office.
That prevented the government

03:00.647 --> 03:06.286 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
from defaulting on its debts
tomorrow. The package also
includes $80 billion in new
spending

03:06.286 --> 03:09.156 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
for defense and
domestic programs.

03:09.156 --> 03:14.027 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: The president also
stepped up his push for criminal
justice reforms today,

03:14.027 --> 03:18.331 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
highlighting efforts to help
former inmates reenter society.

03:18.331 --> 03:23.437 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In Newark, New Jersey, he
announced he's ordering federal
agencies to ban the box on
criminal

03:23.437 --> 03:27.140 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
history that appears
on employment forms.

03:27.140 --> 03:30.577 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BARACK OBAMA, President of the
United States: On many job
applications, there is a box
that

03:30.577 --> 03:37.417 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
asks if you have criminal
record. If you answer yes, then
a lot of times you're not
getting

03:37.417 --> 03:43.824 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a call back. We're going to do
our part in changing this. The
federal government, I believe,

03:43.824 --> 03:48.428 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
shouldn't use criminal history
to screen out applicants, before
we even look at their
qualifications.

03:48.428 --> 03:52.999 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: The president said
roughly 70 million Americans
have some kind of criminal

03:52.999 --> 03:54.734 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
record.

03:54.734 --> 03:59.806 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Two people who
served on a papal reform
commission have been arrested

03:59.806 --> 04:05.178 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
on suspicion they leaked
confidential documents. Vatican
authorities say a Spanish priest
and

04:05.178 --> 04:10.183 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Italian laywoman allegedly
passed the information to
journalists.

04:10.183 --> 04:15.522 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Pope Francis formed the
now-defunct commission in 2013
in an effort to address the
Vatican's

04:15.522 --> 04:19.192 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
secretive and complex
financial holdings.

04:19.192 --> 04:23.296 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GREG BURKE, Vatican Senior
Adviser: Once again, people are
trying to profit from stolen
documents,

04:23.296 --> 04:27.234 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and people with the trust of
Pope Francis have betrayed it,
people that the pope trusted

04:27.234 --> 04:30.303 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in. That's hardly the way
to help his mission.

04:30.303 --> 04:35.075 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Francis'
predecessor, Pope Benedict,
faced a similar document leak in

04:35.075 --> 04:40.280 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
2012 that led to the arrest of
his butler and a Vatican
computer technician.

04:40.280 --> 04:45.919 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: For the first time,
an African-American cleric will
lead the U.S. Episcopal Church.

04:45.919 --> 04:51.791 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Presiding Bishop Michael Curry
was installed Sunday. In the
face of dwindling membership,

04:51.791 --> 04:56.396 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
he urged the nation's two
million Episcopalians to reach
out to those of different racial

04:56.396 --> 05:00.267 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and economic backgrounds. Curry
succeeds Katharine Jefferts
Schori, the first woman to serve

05:00.267 --> 05:02.569 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in the position.

05:02.569 --> 05:07.707 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Wall Street got
the week off to a strong start,
thanks to a rally in health

05:07.707 --> 05:16.316 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
care and energy stocks. The Dow
Jones industrial average gained
165 points to close near 17830,

05:16.316 --> 05:20.654 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
putting it back in positive
territory for the year. The
Nasdaq rose more than 70 points,

05:20.654 --> 05:24.491 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and the S&amp;P 500 added 24.

05:24.491 --> 05:30.163 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: And Kansas City is
celebrating today, after the
Royals won their first World

05:30.163 --> 05:36.403 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Series championship in 30 years.
The Royals rallied last night to
beat the New York Mets,

05:36.403 --> 05:40.874 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
7-to-2, in 12 innings. And that
gave them the title four games
to one.

05:40.874 --> 05:42.375 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: A lot of
celebrating in Kansas City.

05:42.375 --> 05:44.477 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
GWEN IFILL: Yes.

05:44.477 --> 05:49.082 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Still to come on
the "NewsHour": questions abound
in the crash of a Russian

05:49.082 --> 05:54.955 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
airliner; jury selection and
racial discrimination before the
Supreme Court; Jeb Bush tries to

05:54.955 --> 06:03.363 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
jump-start his campaign,
and much more.

06:03.363 --> 06:15.008 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Officials from at
least five countries are
investigating why a Russian
jetliner broke

06:15.008 --> 06:19.412 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
up in midair and crashed
in Egypt this weekend.

06:19.412 --> 06:24.484 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
There are many questions
tonight, but little agreement so
far that may have explained what

06:24.484 --> 06:31.157 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
happened. Wreckage lay strewn
across miles of desert after
Saturday's crash, leaving

06:31.157 --> 06:37.097 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a giant mangled puzzle for
Russian and Egyptian
investigators. They're looking
for any clues

06:37.097 --> 06:43.837 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to what downed the airliner and
killed 224 people, everyone on
board.

06:43.837 --> 06:49.175 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But as a top Russian official at
the scene said yesterday, that
remains far from clear.

06:49.175 --> 06:52.445 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
VIKTOR SOROCHENKO, Investigator
(through translator): Initial
examination showed that, at the
moment,

06:52.445 --> 06:56.549 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
we can't exclude any version of
the crash. We will be looking
into all possibilities.

06:56.549 --> 07:01.421 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: What is known is the
flight took off from the resort
town of Sharm el-Sheikh

07:01.421 --> 07:08.828 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
bound for Saint Petersburg. It
had reached 31,000 feet,
cruising altitude, when it broke

07:08.828 --> 07:15.068 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
up over the Sinai Peninsula,
just 23 minutes after takeoff.
Little else has been confirmed,

07:15.068 --> 07:19.639 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
and conflicting reports
have fed confusion.

07:19.639 --> 07:23.710 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In Moscow today, a senior
official with the Russian
airline Metrojet pointed to some
unnamed

07:23.710 --> 07:27.080 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
external factor.

07:27.080 --> 07:31.618 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALEXANDER SMIRNOV, Metrojet
(through translator): There are
no such faults, like engine
failure,

07:31.618 --> 07:35.922 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
system failure. There is no such
combination of systems failure
that could lead to a plane

07:35.922 --> 07:40.560 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
breaking up in the air. The only
possible explanation for a
breakup of the aircraft

07:40.560 --> 07:44.998 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in the air could be a certain
impact, some mechanical or
physical impact.

07:44.998 --> 07:51.004 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Asked if it was a
terror attack, the official said
only, "Anything is possible."

07:51.004 --> 07:56.976 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But the Russian government's
chief aviation regulator said
all such talk is premature.

07:56.976 --> 08:01.581 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Russians also dismissed a
claim that an Islamic State
affiliate brought down the
plane,

08:01.581 --> 08:04.784 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
saying the group doesn't
have that ability.

08:04.784 --> 08:10.423 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Meanwhile, Reuters reported that
initial data from the black box
recorders shows no sign

08:10.423 --> 08:17.063 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the plane was hit by a missile.
They didn't rule out sabotage or
even a bomb on board.

08:17.063 --> 08:20.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That left Russian President
Vladimir Putin to promise Moscow
will get to the bottom of

08:20.500 --> 08:22.469 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the mystery.

08:22.469 --> 08:25.538 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
VLADIMIR PUTIN, Russian
President (through translator):
Without any doubt, everything

08:25.538 --> 08:28.975 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
has to be done to make sure we
have an objective description of
what happened. We have to know

08:28.975 --> 08:32.812 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
what happened and to react
in the appropriate way.

08:32.812 --> 08:37.884 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: But getting an
objective description from
Russian or Egyptian officials
has proved

08:37.884 --> 08:44.424 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
difficult in previous crashes.
In 1999, an Egypt Air flight
went down off Massachusetts.

08:44.424 --> 08:49.195 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A U.S. investigation found the
co-pilot deliberately flew the
plane into the ocean. But
Egypt's

08:49.195 --> 08:52.665 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
government refused to
accept that finding.

08:52.665 --> 08:59.239 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And, last year, Malaysia
Airlines Flight 17 crashed in
Eastern Ukraine. An
international

08:59.239 --> 09:03.343 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
committee has since determined
that Russian-backed rebels shot
down the plane, a finding that

09:03.343 --> 09:06.679 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Moscow rejected.

09:06.679 --> 09:11.785 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Meanwhile, bodies from this
latest crash have begun arriving
in Saint Petersburg. The city

09:11.785 --> 09:14.454 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
is officially in mourning
through tomorrow.

09:14.454 --> 09:17.190 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So, what do we know so far?

09:17.190 --> 09:21.161 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For more, I'm joined by Alan
Diehl, a former investigator for
the National Transportation

09:21.161 --> 09:26.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Safety Board, and the author of
"Air Safety Investigators: Using
Science to Save Lives."

09:26.800 --> 09:31.304 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Alan Diehl, I want to walk you
through some of the theories we
have heard so far today

09:31.304 --> 09:38.411 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and which we heard just now in
that tape. Let's talk first
about the complete midair

09:38.411 --> 09:42.782 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
collision or failure. What
is the possibility of that?

09:42.782 --> 09:46.052 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ALAN DIEHL, Former National
Transportation Safety Board
Investigator: Well, the wreckage

09:46.052 --> 09:52.625 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
-- the wreckage location pattern
suggests that there was some
kind of inside breakup,

09:52.625 --> 09:57.263 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
but I don't think this happened
at 31,000 feet, even though it
spread over several miles.

09:57.263 --> 10:01.901 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That's a fairly tight pattern,
and there's been report that the
data was streaming as

10:01.901 --> 10:08.141 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
low as -- down to as low as
5,000 feet. So the problem may
have began at 31,000 feet,

10:08.141 --> 10:12.912 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
but I believe the aircraft was
relatively intact down to lower
altitudes, perhaps as

10:12.912 --> 10:15.882 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
low as 5,000 feet.

10:15.882 --> 10:21.087 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, we do know the tail is
three miles from the main
wreckage and there is other
debris

10:21.087 --> 10:26.826 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and bodies scattered in the
area, but I don't think this
aircraft came apart, like, for

10:26.826 --> 10:32.131 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
example, the Malaysia 17 flight
did when it was hit by a large
missile over Ukraine.

10:32.131 --> 10:35.735 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
GWEN IFILL: So it's not
consistent with a midair
explosion, at least not at that
height?

10:35.735 --> 10:39.672 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
ALAN DIEHL: I would
say not, Gwen.

10:39.672 --> 10:45.278 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, of course, having done this
40 years, everything is very
preliminary and I can only

10:45.278 --> 10:52.585 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
speculate. I think the Egyptians
will do a very thorough job. We
know that, oftentimes,

10:52.585 --> 10:56.289 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
people say this is like putting
a jigsaw puzzle together. Only,
many times, you don't have

10:56.289 --> 10:58.858 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
all the pieces.

10:58.858 --> 11:05.632 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think we have got all the
pieces right now. The recorders
were in good shape. The
Egyptians

11:05.632 --> 11:10.737 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
had analyzed those. I think that
was why they discounted the
missile strike theory. And,

11:10.737 --> 11:16.409 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of course, the wreckage is in a
desert area. This is not like
the Ukrainian crash, where

11:16.409 --> 11:20.647 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it was scattered over a very
wide area. People were pilfering
things, we think, and maybe

11:20.647 --> 11:23.182 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
even the rebels were
removing things.

11:23.182 --> 11:27.921 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So I think we have got all the
parts of this jigsaw puzzle, but
it's going to take a little

11:27.921 --> 11:33.927 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
time for all the players to come
together. It's not just the
Russians that are doing

11:33.927 --> 11:36.396 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the investigation. We're using
the Egyptians. We know there are
five countries.

11:36.396 --> 11:38.197 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
GWEN IFILL: Right.

11:38.197 --> 11:40.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ALAN DIEHL: And particularly
with the French involved, I
think we're going to get to the

11:40.466 --> 11:43.036 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
bottom of this, and
fairly expeditiously.

11:43.036 --> 11:46.506 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: You mentioned the
fact that the plane's tail was
some distance away from a

11:46.506 --> 11:49.175 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
lot of the other wreckage.

11:49.175 --> 11:52.979 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There's also -- there were also
reports today that there had
been damage to the plane's

11:52.979 --> 11:59.218 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
tail some years ago that had
been repaired. What's the
potential for some sort of
weakness

11:59.218 --> 12:04.791 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
or metal stress and failure
which would have created
something this catastrophic?

12:04.791 --> 12:11.965 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ALAN DIEHL: Well, we have seen
this before. In a 747 over
Japan, the worst single aircraft

12:11.965 --> 12:16.903 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
accident in the history, killed
520 people, the tail came off,
because a -- they're called

12:16.903 --> 12:21.941 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
tail strikes. The aircraft tail
bumps the ground on takeoff or
landing.

12:21.941 --> 12:26.846 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So this is a real possibility.
But, again, Gwen, they have the
physical evidence, and

12:26.846 --> 12:30.683 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the Egyptians seem to be doing a
very good job of protecting
that. I have noticed they

12:30.683 --> 12:34.887 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
have even put fences around the
primary wreckage location.

12:34.887 --> 12:40.460 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, the metallurgists will haul
that tail back into the lab and,
with electron microscopes

12:40.460 --> 12:45.665 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and other techniques, establish
whether this repair was done
correctly or whether there

12:45.665 --> 12:51.804 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
was some sort of metal fatigue
involved or even a catastrophic
failure for some other

12:51.804 --> 12:55.274 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
reason. I think we will get to
the bottom of this when we have
the evidence.

12:55.274 --> 12:58.578 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Well, the black box,
is that essential for us to find
out whether maybe pilot error

12:58.578 --> 12:59.545 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
could have been involved?

12:59.545 --> 13:02.281 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ALAN DIEHL: Absolutely.

13:02.281 --> 13:08.254 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, of course, as many people
have said, everything is still
on the table. Another

13:08.254 --> 13:12.492 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
thing that was very curious
about this, and, again, these
are initial reports confirmed

13:12.492 --> 13:18.331 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I guess by the Egyptians, that
the radar data suggested that
the plane didn't just suddenly

13:18.331 --> 13:24.937 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
dive out of the sky from 31,000
feet, that it actually entered a
series of undulations

13:24.937 --> 13:30.009 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
where it climbed and dived --
dove a couple thousand feet
before it made its final plunge

13:30.009 --> 13:33.046 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
toward the desert.

13:33.046 --> 13:37.283 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, that could -- we have seen
this in the past with these
highly automated aircraft,

13:37.283 --> 13:43.756 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
where pilots have been confused
and perhaps shut down the wrong
system. The automation

13:43.756 --> 13:49.962 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is fed by other sensors. And
sometimes these sensors, like in
the Air France accident in

13:49.962 --> 13:54.200 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the South Atlantic, they -- in
essence, they're feeding
erroneous data to the computers
and

13:54.200 --> 13:59.238 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the computers do things that
cause the pilots to be confused
and contribute to this.

13:59.238 --> 14:03.409 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now, you can argue that's pilot
error or design error. Take your
pick. The lawyers will sort

14:03.409 --> 14:06.212 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
all that out in future
years, I guess.

14:06.212 --> 14:09.148 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Alan Diehl, aviation
security consultant, thank you
for helping us.

14:09.148 --> 14:18.191 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ALAN DIEHL: Thank you, Gwen.

14:18.191 --> 14:28.801 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And now we turn
to the Supreme Court, where
justices heard arguments in a

14:28.801 --> 14:32.004 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
death penalty case out of
Georgia that deals with race
discrimination in the selection

14:32.004 --> 14:34.173 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of jurors.

14:34.173 --> 14:38.144 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We begin our coverage of that
case with a version of a report
that originally aired

14:38.144 --> 14:41.614 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
on the PBS program "Religion
&amp; Ethics Newsweekly."

14:41.614 --> 14:44.751 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Correspondent Tim
O'Brien has the story.

14:44.751 --> 14:50.757 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TIM O'BRIEN: It was in 1986 in
Rome, Georgia.
Seventy-nine-year-old Queen
White had just

14:50.757 --> 14:57.296 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
returned home from choir
practice to confront a burglar
who would take her life.

14:57.296 --> 15:03.069 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Prosecutors said it was this man
-- Timothy Foster -- 18 years
old at the time.

15:03.069 --> 15:05.271 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Down at the Floyd County
Courthouse, over the vehement
objections of defense lawyers,

15:05.271 --> 15:10.643 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
prosecutors excused all
African-Americans from the jury
pool. Foster would be tried,

15:10.643 --> 15:16.182 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
convicted, and sentenced to
die by an all-white jury.

15:16.182 --> 15:20.753 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The U.S. Supreme Court had ruled
only four months before this
crime was committed that

15:20.753 --> 15:26.025 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
while lawyers have wide latitude
in selecting juries and may even
excuse some prospective

15:26.025 --> 15:31.397 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
jurors without having to explain
why, race can never be a factor.
Should it appear that

15:31.397 --> 15:36.669 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
race is the motive, the attorney
must be able to provide
race-neutral reasons.

15:36.669 --> 15:37.737 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
STEPHEN BRIGHT, President and
Senior Counsel, Southern Center
for Human Rights: The reasons

15:37.737 --> 15:42.975 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
given here -- some were false.
They just simply weren't true.
Some were contradictory. In

15:42.975 --> 15:48.047 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
fact, on their lists of people
who they were definitely going
to strike, the five
African-Americans

15:48.047 --> 15:51.050 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
were the first five listed. And
there was only one other person
on the list, and it

15:51.050 --> 15:53.352 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
was a white woman.

15:53.352 --> 15:57.523 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
TIM O'BRIEN: Stephen Bright runs
the Southern Center for Human
Rights in Atlanta and will

15:57.523 --> 16:03.362 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
argue Foster's case before the
Supreme Court. Proving jurors
were removed because of their

16:03.362 --> 16:07.600 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
race can be difficult, but
lawyers at the Center say they
have come up with some
persuasive

16:07.600 --> 16:09.936 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
new evidence.

16:09.936 --> 16:12.638 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
STEPHEN BRIGHT: In the
prosecutor's files, they had
listed -- they race-coded and
color-coded

16:12.638 --> 16:17.076 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
all the black people in
the lists of the jurors.

16:17.076 --> 16:22.281 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They had compared the black
jurors against each other in the
notes, saying, "If we have

16:22.281 --> 16:26.052 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to accept a black, maybe this
one would be OK," which suggests
the goal was to get rid

16:26.052 --> 16:32.058 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of all the blacks. And so it all
points pretty much in one
direction, which is race.

16:32.058 --> 16:38.631 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
TIM O'BRIEN: A 10-year study of
332 criminal cases in Louisiana
found that when there were

16:38.631 --> 16:43.569 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
at least three blacks on the
jury, 12 percent of the
defendants were acquitted; the
acquittal

16:43.569 --> 16:50.109 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
rate rose to 19 percent with
five or more black jurors, and
no one was acquitted in

16:50.109 --> 16:54.213 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the study when there were two or
fewer black jurors. In all three
groups, the defendants

16:54.213 --> 16:58.184 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
were overwhelmingly black.

16:58.184 --> 17:03.189 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Kent Scheidegger is legal
director of the Criminal Justice
Legal Foundation, victims'

17:03.189 --> 17:08.294 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
rights group that supports
capital punishment, and
Scheidegger says the fact that
prosecutors

17:08.294 --> 17:12.932 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
kept notes on the race of the
jurors doesn't prove racial
discrimination, but rather may

17:12.932 --> 17:15.334 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
help to refute it.

17:15.334 --> 17:17.536 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
KENT SCHEIDEGGER, Legal
Director, Criminal Justice Legal
Foundation: The fact that you

17:17.536 --> 17:23.576 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
keep track of the race of the
jurors as you go through the
process is not at all
suspicious.

17:23.576 --> 17:28.314 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In order to defend yourself
against the charges of
discrimination, you have to keep
track.

17:28.314 --> 17:32.418 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That's why every time we apply
for a loan, or a job, or school
admission, we're asked

17:32.418 --> 17:35.721 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to specify our race, and that's
all they were doing in this
case.

17:35.721 --> 17:41.961 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEPHEN BRIGHT: If all you
wanted was to know information
about the black jurors, you
wouldn't

17:41.961 --> 17:47.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
write things like, "If we have
to accept a black, maybe this
one will be OK."

17:47.300 --> 17:48.701 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
TIM O'BRIEN: You want his
conviction set aside.

17:48.701 --> 17:50.069 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
KENT SCHEIDEGGER: Right.

17:50.069 --> 17:53.239 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
TIM O'BRIEN: But what more than
that? What do you want the court
to say?

17:53.239 --> 17:57.109 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
STEPHEN BRIGHT: One of the
things that I hope at the very
least will come out of this case

17:57.109 --> 18:02.715 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is that the court will require
the reasons given be scrutinized
much more carefully than

18:02.715 --> 18:05.785 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
they were in this case.

18:05.785 --> 18:11.624 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
TIM O'BRIEN: Significantly, last
June, two justices formally
urged the court to reconsider

18:11.624 --> 18:15.594 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
whether the United States is
even capable of administering
capital punishment in a
constitutional

18:15.594 --> 18:18.164 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
manner.

18:18.164 --> 18:23.569 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The justices, Stephen Breyer,
joined by Ruth Bader Ginsburg,
noted that the risk of executing

18:23.569 --> 18:29.442 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
an innocent person remains
great, that factors such as
race, gender, and geography make
the

18:29.442 --> 18:35.681 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
death penalty arbitrary, that
the decades-long delays between
sentence and execution defeat

18:35.681 --> 18:41.620 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the goals of deterrence and
retribution, and that both death
sentences and actual executions

18:41.620 --> 18:47.660 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
are becoming increasingly
unusual -- down almost 70
percent in the last 15 years.

18:47.660 --> 18:51.597 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEPHEN BREYER, Associate
Justice, U.S. Supreme Court: I
recognize that we are a court,
not

18:51.597 --> 18:57.269 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a legislature, but the matters
that I have discussed are
judicial matters. They concern

18:57.269 --> 19:06.579 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the infliction of an unfair,
cruel, and unusual punishment
upon individuals at odds with a

19:06.579 --> 19:13.552 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
specific constraint that the
Constitution imposes on the
democratic process."

19:13.552 --> 19:20.126 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TIM O'BRIEN: The country appears
to be slowly, but inexorably,
moving away from capital
punishment.

19:20.126 --> 19:24.997 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
If so, the U.S. Supreme Court
may not be too far behind.

19:24.997 --> 19:30.436 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: The justices also
heard a case looking at the
issue of online privacy.

19:30.436 --> 19:33.639 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For more on both cases, we turn
to Marcia Coyle of "The National
Law Journal," who was

19:33.639 --> 19:35.541 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
at the Supreme Court today.

19:35.541 --> 19:37.977 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So, welcome back, Marcia.

19:37.977 --> 19:38.811 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARCIA COYLE, "The National
Law Journal": Thank you.

19:38.811 --> 19:43.783 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Let's talk first
about the all-white jury case.
How important is it that

19:43.783 --> 19:49.555 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the lawyers of this accused man,
Timothy Foster, were able to get
ahold of those original notes

19:49.555 --> 19:53.192 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
made by the prosecutor
back in 1987?

19:53.192 --> 19:57.730 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARCIA COYLE: Well, Judy, I
think how the justices view the
notes is really crucial

19:57.730 --> 20:02.701 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
to Mr. Foster's chance
of getting a new trial.

20:02.701 --> 20:09.075 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
If the justices see race
discrimination in those notes,
that is a violation of the 14th

20:09.075 --> 20:11.911 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Amendment, and he
will get a new trial.

20:11.911 --> 20:13.579 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So tell us about
the arguments before the court
today.

20:13.579 --> 20:15.714 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MARCIA COYLE: Sure.

20:15.714 --> 20:20.719 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
During the arguments, Mr.
Foster's attorney, Steve Bright,
argued that the notes
represented

20:20.719 --> 20:27.860 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
an arsenal of smoking guns that
were designed clearly to
separate the African-American
prospective

20:27.860 --> 20:31.864 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
jurors and to treat
them differently.

20:31.864 --> 20:38.771 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Justice Kagan asked Georgia's
attorney why this wasn't as
clear violation of the court's

20:38.771 --> 20:45.845 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
1986 decision as the court was
ever likely to see. And
Georgia's attorney said, well,

20:45.845 --> 20:51.617 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
really, the notes can be viewed
in two ways. They could be
viewed as the prosecutors'
preparation

20:51.617 --> 20:56.422 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to defend against the claim
of racial discrimination.

20:56.422 --> 21:02.128 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Justice Breyer said that was
hard to believe because that
reason, he said, was never given

21:02.128 --> 21:07.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
by the prosecutor until the case
actually came to the Supreme
Court. So it appeared

21:07.500 --> 21:12.304 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that there were a number of
justices sympathetic to Mr.
Foster's claim.

21:12.304 --> 21:15.307 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, the justices
would push back when the lawyers
for the state of Georgia

21:15.307 --> 21:16.342 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
made that argument?

21:16.342 --> 21:18.777 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MARCIA COYLE: That's right.

21:18.777 --> 21:24.416 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I should mention, Judy, that
there is a possibility that the
court will not reach the merits
here.

21:24.416 --> 21:29.088 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There is a procedural problem
with the case that came up very
late, and the case may have

21:29.088 --> 21:32.658 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to go back to the Georgia
Supreme Court for some
clarification.

21:32.658 --> 21:36.729 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, what we said
earlier in the program about
there being wider implications

21:36.729 --> 21:40.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for this case, that really does
on what the -- how the justices
choose to look at this.

21:40.633 --> 21:42.468 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
MARCIA COYLE: It does
absolutely. It could be narrow,
focused solely on Mr. Foster's

21:42.468 --> 21:44.837 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
case.

21:44.837 --> 21:49.975 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But even if he wins, and it is
narrow, it sends a message, I
think, to other courts

21:49.975 --> 21:57.583 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to look at these kinds of claims
very carefully. In 1986, Justice
Thurgood Marshall wrote
separately

21:57.583 --> 22:04.890 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in the case to say that the
Batson rule here that was
announced by the court in '86
wasn't

22:04.890 --> 22:09.628 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
likely to end race
discrimination in jury
selection. The only way to end
it was to eliminate

22:09.628 --> 22:11.797 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
discretionary jury strikes.

22:11.797 --> 22:14.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
There doesn't seem to be
much sympathy for that.

22:14.833 --> 22:18.437 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, let's talk
now about this other case the
justices heard today.

22:18.437 --> 22:24.343 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This had to do with incorrect
information on a search engine
about somebody on the Internet

22:24.343 --> 22:27.580 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and whether this constituted
real harm done to this person.
Tell us about the core of

22:27.580 --> 22:28.380 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
this case.

22:28.380 --> 22:30.816 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MARCIA COYLE: OK.

22:30.816 --> 22:36.589 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Well, Spokeo is a -- calls
itself a people search engine.
It collects information on

22:36.589 --> 22:42.394 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
individuals, and that
information is used in credit
reports and for other purposes.

22:42.394 --> 22:48.434 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Tom Robins, he searched for his
name on Spokeo, and, frankly,
the information there was a

22:48.434 --> 22:52.004 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
mess. They got wrong his age,
his marital status, his
education, his employment,
whether

22:52.004 --> 22:52.972 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
he had children.

22:52.972 --> 22:53.672 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Just
about everything.

22:53.672 --> 22:55.841 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
MARCIA COYLE: Just
about everything.

22:55.841 --> 23:02.648 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, the Fair Credit Reporting
Act imposes a series of
regulatory requirements on
credit

23:02.648 --> 23:08.554 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
reporting agencies. Congress
passed it to ensure maximum
accuracy in the reporting of

23:08.554 --> 23:13.626 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
this information. And it
provides limited damages if the
act is violated, either
negligently

23:13.626 --> 23:16.495 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
or willfully.

