actually played across the...

45:51.916 --> 45:52.483 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

45:52.483 --> 45:54.418 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Never
happened, right?

45:54.418 --> 45:55.686 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ELVIS COSTELLO: No, they had
never been out of the
neighborhood.

45:55.686 --> 45:57.989 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So, he was
sort of making it up.

45:57.989 --> 46:01.192 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ELVIS COSTELLO: Well, that was
good. That was the dream of it,
to do that.

46:01.192 --> 46:08.332 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The father would
go on to a successful singing
career with one of Britain's

46:08.332 --> 46:16.741 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
leading dance bands, doing cover
songs of popular music, even
folk songs like "If I

46:16.741 --> 46:22.013 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Had a Hammer."

46:22.013 --> 46:35.092 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The son, born Declan MacManus,
would become one of the leading
rockers of his time, emerging

46:35.092 --> 46:38.262 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in the late 1970s as a kind of
nerdy-looking, language-loving,
angry young songwriter and

46:38.262 --> 46:45.403 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
singer.

46:45.403 --> 46:49.807 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He was pegged back then as part
of the folk scene. But when we
talked recently at New

46:49.807 --> 46:54.178 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
York's famous Village Vanguard,
a nod to his jazz-loving dad,
recently, Costello said he

46:54.178 --> 46:57.448 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
never saw himself that way.

46:57.448 --> 47:03.788 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ELVIS COSTELLO: I think, early
on, I had worked out that if I
adopted a sort of less
cooperative

47:03.788 --> 47:06.123 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
personality when speaking to
people, they would leave me
alone. And I would just be

47:06.123 --> 47:06.424 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
able to get...

47:06.424 --> 47:06.991 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

47:06.991 --> 47:08.959 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
JEFFREY BROWN:
Simple as that, huh?

47:08.959 --> 47:12.530 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ELVIS COSTELLO: I just created
this character accidentally. And
then I realized, hey, that

47:12.530 --> 47:12.963 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
works.

47:12.963 --> 47:14.965 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

47:14.965 --> 47:18.469 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ELVIS COSTELLO: It gets kind of
tedious to kind of keep it up,
because then you can never

47:18.469 --> 47:21.806 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
drop it down. You can never drop
it down and just laugh, you
know?

47:21.806 --> 47:23.874 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Well, that's what
I'm wondering. But you think of
it as a character?

47:23.874 --> 47:25.710 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

47:25.710 --> 47:28.913 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
ELVIS COSTELLO: Not in a
calculated way. It just happened
spontaneously. And then you

47:28.913 --> 47:31.382 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
see the effect and then you
play into the effect. But...

47:31.382 --> 47:36.320 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The book sort of
tells the story of you becoming
more yourself or allowing

47:36.320 --> 47:41.125 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
yourself to be less of that
character and more who you
actually are?

47:41.125 --> 47:48.265 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ELVIS COSTELLO: I think it's a
process of, you know, adventure,
misadventure, you know,

47:48.265 --> 47:54.004 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
failure personally, and then
realizing that you can't keep
doing -- you know, it's not

47:54.004 --> 48:01.011 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
like I'm denying the nature of
the songs, but just carrying on
like that was just tiring.

48:01.011 --> 48:07.251 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's just like you run out of
drinks to drink, you know, that
kind of thing? And then there

48:07.251 --> 48:10.788 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
were just other songs to sing
and other lives to live.

48:10.788 --> 48:15.693 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Over the years,
other songs came, many of them,
as Costello took on a

48:15.693 --> 48:44.688 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
wide range of other styles of
music, an album with Burt
Bacharach, one with a string
quartet,

48:44.688 --> 48:48.092 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and much more to this day.

48:48.092 --> 48:54.632 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But it began, he writes, at home
as a child, when his father was
passing on records that

48:54.632 --> 48:59.837 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
he was listening to for his own
work and both parents had
eclectic tastes.

48:59.837 --> 49:04.108 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ELVIS COSTELLO: I didn't study
any French, so I didn't know the
word genre. You know,

49:04.108 --> 49:09.980 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
so I didn't have sort of a sense
of there being different kinds
of music.

49:09.980 --> 49:15.419 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And my dad would get passions
for Bach and we would listen all
to the Bach passion, and

49:15.419 --> 49:22.927 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
then the Clancy Brothers and
Irish music. And my mother loved
singers like Sinatra and

49:22.927 --> 49:28.065 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Ella Fitzgerald. So I heard all
those songs, as well as all the
1960s pop music that came

49:28.065 --> 49:33.003 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
out, whether it would be from
England like the Beatles or from
America like Motown.

49:33.003 --> 49:37.441 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it was all just flowing
through. And it didn't seem like
you had to choose.

49:37.441 --> 49:42.313 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: What about when
it came to performing and
putting yourself forward?
There's

49:42.313 --> 49:46.250 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the -- and even taking a new
name, right, and not only just a
new name, but a very big

49:46.250 --> 49:47.117 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
name, Elvis.

49:47.117 --> 49:49.386 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ELVIS COSTELLO: Yes.

49:49.386 --> 49:55.259 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Well, I just felt, well, my
family name, McManus, is hard to
say on the telephone. It didn't

49:55.259 --> 50:00.331 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
look very attractive written
down. It sort of suggested a guy
in a cable-knit sweater

50:00.331 --> 50:05.169 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
singing waling songs. And so I
wanted something a little
groovier.

50:05.169 --> 50:10.574 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So I had adopted that part. And
in addition, my father had made
records in the '60s under

50:10.574 --> 50:14.545 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
assumed names, because he had
made money on the side from his
contracted gig as a dance

50:14.545 --> 50:15.112 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
band singer.

50:15.112 --> 50:16.747 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes.

50:16.747 --> 50:18.983 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ELVIS COSTELLO: He had made
records under the names Frank
Bacon and the Baconeers and

50:18.983 --> 50:19.783 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Hal Prince and the Layabouts.

50:19.783 --> 50:21.118 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

50:21.118 --> 50:23.520 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So, you're used
to taking on any names, but...

50:23.520 --> 50:25.022 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

50:25.022 --> 50:26.457 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ELVIS COSTELLO: Seemed like, in
the noble showbiz, tradition, if
you're going to, you

50:26.457 --> 50:28.659 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
know -- I mean, you know.

50:28.659 --> 50:32.630 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The memoir moves
back and forth through time,
connecting, as Costello told

50:32.630 --> 50:37.201 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
me, moments, experiences,
revelations.

50:37.201 --> 50:42.306 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But it's all there, the way up
working with many of today's
great musicians and the many

50:42.306 --> 50:46.443 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
downs, broken marriages, too
much drinking, a loss of control
over what he wanted to be

50:46.443 --> 50:48.212 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
doing.

50:48.212 --> 50:53.183 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ELVIS COSTELLO: You can be
addicted to misery the same way
as you can be addicted to drugs.

50:53.183 --> 50:54.385 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

50:54.385 --> 50:57.788 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And you felt
yourself addicted to misery in a
sense?

50:57.788 --> 51:03.127 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ELVIS COSTELLO: I am a fairly
decent, dark-dispositioned
person, have been, but you can
-- it can start

51:03.127 --> 51:07.231 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to like it, rather than sort of
try to think, well, yes, I'm --
I was fine being a skeptic,

51:07.231 --> 51:10.234 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
but then when you start to
settle for that, then it's not
very good.

51:10.234 --> 51:14.438 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: But he also sings
of happier times, including his
marriage to the jazz

51:14.438 --> 51:32.890 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
